an original archive of children’s sexual and embodied experiences. Zaborskis argues that these boarding schools—designed to segregate racialized, criminalized, and disabled children from mainstream culture—produced new forms of childhood. These childhoods have secured American futures in which institutionalized children (and the adults they become) have not been considered full-fledged citizens or participants. By locating this queerness in state archives and institutions, Queer Childhoods exposes a queer social history entangled with genocide, eugenics, and racialized violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren of minoritiesxInstitutional care. 0aGay youth. 0aQueer theory. 0aSexual minoritiesxIdentity. 0aSexual minority youthxInstitutional care. 0aSexual minority youth. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh  aAfrican American industrial schools.  aCarlisle Industrial School.  aClaude Brown.  aCree.  aHistory of disability.  aHistory of disabled children.  aInstitutionalizing children.  aManassas Industrial School.  aNative American boarding schools.  aPerkins School for the Blind.  aRuth Hayden.  aSherman Alexie.  aTarrell Alvin McCraney.  aTomson Highway.  aWiltwyck School for Boys.  abiopolitical.  abiopolitics.  aboarding schools and disability.  aboarding schools.  abooks about disabled children.  abooks about institutionalized children.  adisabled children.  aeugenics.  agenocide.  ahistory of biopolitics.  ahistory of boarding schools.  ahistory of education.  ahistory of queer childhoods.  ainstitutionalized children.  ajuvenile delinquency.  aqueer childhoods.  aqueer theory.  aracial violence against children.  aracialized violence.  areform schools.  aschools for the blind.08iTitle is part of eBook packag